## pgmq — Message Queues in Postgres

**When you need it**: Background job processing, async embedding generation, retry logic for failed operations.

### Enable
```sql
CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgmq WITH SCHEMA public;
```

### Basic queue operations
```sql
-- Create a queue
SELECT pgmq.create('embeddings_queue');

-- Send a message
SELECT pgmq.send('embeddings_queue', '{"document_id": 123, "content": "Hello world"}');

-- Read messages (visibility timeout: 30 seconds)
SELECT * FROM pgmq.read('embeddings_queue', 30, 10);  -- 10 messages max

-- Delete a message after processing
SELECT pgmq.delete('embeddings_queue', [msg_id]);

-- Archive instead of delete (keeps history)
SELECT pgmq.archive('embeddings_queue', [msg_id]);
```

### Auto-embedding with pgmq + pg_cron pattern
```sql
-- 1. Create trigger to queue embedding jobs
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION queue_embedding_job()
RETURNS TRIGGER LANGUAGE plpgsql AS $$
BEGIN
  PERFORM pgmq.send('embeddings_queue',
    jsonb_build_object('id', NEW.id, 'content', NEW.content)
  );
  RETURN NEW;
END;
$$;

-- 2. Schedule processor every 10 seconds (calls an Edge Function)
SELECT cron.schedule('process-embeddings', '*/10 * * * * *',
  $$SELECT net.http_post(
    url := 'https://[REF].functions.supabase.co/generate-embeddings',
    headers := '{"Authorization": "Bearer [ANON_KEY]"}'::JSONB,
    body := '{"batch_size": 10}'::JSONB
  )$$
);
```

